dhcpcd Configuration for Static IP (Raspberry Pi)

The dhcpcd service controls IP assignment on Raspberry Pi OS. By editing its configuration file, you can assign a static IP address to ensure your Pi always uses the same address on the network.

1. Open dhcpcd.conf
sudo nano /etc/dhcpcd.conf

2. Add Static IP Settings

Scroll to the bottom and add (adjust values for your network):

For Ethernet (eth0):
interface eth0
static ip_address=192.168.0.105/24
static routers=192.168.0.1
static domain_name_servers=8.8.8.8 8.8.4.4

For Wi-Fi (wlan0):
interface wlan0
static ip_address=192.168.0.110/24
static routers=192.168.0.1
static domain_name_servers=1.1.1.1 8.8.8.8

3. Explanation of Fields

interface → Network interface (eth0 = Ethernet, wlan0 = Wi-Fi).

static ip_address → Desired IP address + subnet (e.g., /24 = 255.255.255.0).

static routers → Gateway IP (usually your router’s IP, e.g., 192.168.0.1).

static domain_name_servers → DNS servers (Google: 8.8.8.8, Cloudflare: 1.1.1.1).

4. Restart Networking
sudo systemctl restart dhcpcd


Or reboot:

sudo reboot

5. Verify

Check assigned IP:

hostname -I


Confirm connectivity:

ping 192.168.0.1
ping google.com
